===Etymology===
1437, from {{etyl|frm}} {{term|funerailles||funeral rites|lang=frm}} {{p}}, from {{etyl|ML.}} {{term|funeralia||funeral rites|lang=la}}, originally neuter plural of {{etyl|LL.}} {{term|funeralis||having to do with a funeral|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|funere|lang=la}}, ablative of {{term|funus||funeral, death, corpse|lang=la}}, origin unknown, perhaps ultimately from {{proto|Indo-European|dheu-|to die}}. Singular and plural used interchangeably in English until circa 1700. The adjective {{term|funereal|lang=en}} is first attested 1725, by influence of {{etyl|frm}} {{term|funerail|lang=frm}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|funereus|lang=la}}, from {{term|funus|lang=la}}.

